There are n children standing in a line. Each child is assigned a rating value given in the integer array ratings.

You are giving candies to these children subjected to the following requirements:

Each child must have at least one candy.
Children with a higher rating get more candies than their neighbors.
Return the minimum number of candies you need to have to distribute the candies to the children.





Intuition - I created this solution myself, nothing extraordinary just little different


Like every other solution, we are going left to right and then right to left and just adding current value with previus iterated value if  it is bigger.
But this will create spikes in positions where both the neighbours are smaller


Ex - ratings - [1, 3, 2, 2, 1] ater both iterations we will get an array [1, 3, 1, 2, 1]. On the first index the candy alloted should  be 2. 

To fix this issue we implement a 3rd loop which will erase these spikes. We culd have done it inside second loop but it will complicate the code.

If we find an index where the difference in candies with its neighbour is more than 1. We will just change that index value to just more than 1 than its neighbour.






class Solution {
    public int candy(int[] rating) {
        int n=rating.length;
        int[] res=new int[n];
        Arrays.fill(res,1);
        
        for(int i=1; i<n; i++){
            if(rating[i]>rating[i-1]){
                res[i] += res[i-1];
            }
        }
        for(int i=n-2; i>=0; i--){

            if(rating[i] > rating[i+1]){
                res[i] += res[i+1];
            }
        }
        for(int i=1; i<n-1; i++){
            if (res[i] - Math.max(res[i-1], res[i+1]) > 1){
                res[i] = Math.max(res[i-1], res[i+1]) + 1;
            }
        }
        return Arrays.stream(res).sum();
    }




Can be done in 2 loops also



class Solution { 
    public int candy(int[] rating) { 
        int n = rating.length; 
        int[] res = new int[n]; 
        Arrays.fill(res, 1); 
        
        for (int i = 1; i < n; i++) { 
            if (rating[i] > rating[i - 1]) { 
                res[i] += res[i - 1]; 
            } 
        } 
        
        for (int i = n - 2; i >= 0; i--) { 

            if (rating[i] > rating[i + 1]) { 
                res[i] += res[i + 1]; 
            }
            int leftNeighbor = (i > 0) ? res[i - 1] : 0;
            int rightNeighbor = res[i + 1];
            
            if (res[i] - Math.max(leftNeighbor, rightNeighbor) > 1) { 
                res[i] = Math.max(leftNeighbor, rightNeighbor) + 1; 
            } 
        } 
        
        return Arrays.stream(res).sum(); 
    } 
}
